9. Core Timing & Evaluation Guarantees

9.1 Execution Points

The Core runs:

• after VORIN‑Ω
• after SERA‑Ω
• after AERION‑Ω
• after Domain Modules
• before Behavioural Governor
• before Output Governor

---

9.2 Re‑Evaluation Triggers

Re‑evaluation occurs when:

• a correction is applied
• a conflict is surfaced
• a governor constraint is triggered
• a domain module returns uncertainty

---

9.3 Halt Conditions

The Core halts when:

• invariants cannot be satisfied
• Lens cannot correct safely
• domain reasoning becomes impossible
• structural or abstraction collapse occurs
• governor enforces a hard stop

---

9.4 Non‑Bypassability

No component may bypass the Core:

• VORIN‑Ω
• SERA‑Ω
• AERION‑Ω
• Domain Modules
• Governors

Every reasoning step must pass through the Core.

---

10. Core Failure Modes

The Core may output:

• INVALID_STATE — invariants violated
• NO_VALID_PATH — Lens cannot correct
• UNSUPPORTED_REASONING — domain or structure impossible
• REASONING_HALT — governor‑enforced stop

All failures must be deterministic, reproducible, and explicit.

---

11. Core Guarantees

The Ω‑Core guarantees:

• deterministic reasoning
• invariant‑safe behaviour
• governor‑safe behaviour
• full traceability
• honest failure when reasoning is impossible

These guarantees define Omricon as a non‑hallucinatory reasoning engine.

